# Notebook Structure (Numbered Sections)

All Jupyter notebooks must be organized into clear, **numbered** markdown headings separating each high-level section.

## Rules

- Start with a level-1 heading: `# <Notebook Title>`
- Use level-2 headings for top-level sections, numbered `0.`, `1.`, `2.` ... in order: `## 0. Imports & Config`
- If a section needs subsections, use level-3 headings with compound numbering: `### 2.1 <Subsection>`
- Keep numbering stable (avoid renumbering churn); only insert new sections as decimals (e.g. `2.1`, `2.2`) when helpful
- Each top-level section should contain at least one cell (markdown or code) and be logically self-contained

## Example notebook template

## 0. Imports & Config
## 1. Data Loading
## 2. Data Cleaning & Engineering
## 3. Modeling / Signal Construction
## 4. Evaluation (plots, metrics, sanity checks)

## Alphalens tear sheets (factor-test notebooks)

When a notebook runs `al.tears.create_full_tear_sheet` (or an equivalent full tear helper):

1. **Display and save** — show the tear in-notebook **and** write a multi-page **PDF**.
2. **Directory** — `02_research/notebooks/factor_tests/tearsheets/` (create with `os.makedirs(..., exist_ok=True)` if missing).
3. **Filename** — `H-XXX_{factor_col}.pdf` where `H-XXX` is the hypothesis id and `factor_col` is the exact panel column (stem + window/mode arguments), e.g. `H-002_gk_vol_reversal_5_63.pdf`, `H-004_residual_mom_126_21.pdf`.
4. **Capture pattern** — Alphalens calls `plt.show()` after each plot (clears figures under Agg). Temporarily replace `plt.show` so each figure with axes is written into the PDF via `matplotlib.backends.backend_pdf.PdfPages` before `plt.close("all")`. Restore `plt.show` in a `finally` block.
5. **Re-runs** overwrite the same path. Do not auto-tear every screened column unless the user asks (runtime).

Define `TEARSHEET_DIR` next to other paths in `## 0. Imports & Config`. Import `matplotlib` / `pyplot` / `PdfPages` there (or in the evaluation helpers cell).